\title{GF(3) as Crystalline Structure}
\taxon{bridge}
\author{monaduck1069}
\date{2026-03-30}
\tag{cross-reference}
\tag{bci}
\tag{gf3}
\tag{crystalline}

\p{The GF(3) conservation law threading the BCI pipeline has a natural interpretation in crystalline cohomology and the de Rham--Witt complex.}

\p{\strong{The trit field #{\mathbb{F}_3}}:}
\ul{
  \li{Three rooms: bci.blue (-1), bci.red (+1), bci.place (0). Sum = 0 in #{\mathbb{F}_3}.}
  \li{Four stages: each preserves the trit sum modulo 3.}
  \li{SplitMix64 deterministic hash maps names to colors in #{\mathbb{F}_3}-balanced triads.}
}

\p{\strong{Stacks Project connections}:}
\ul{
  \li{[[stk-0060]] \strong{Crystalline Cohomology} --- Over #{\mathbb{F}_3}, the crystalline site provides a lift of the trit structure to characteristic zero. The Frobenius action on #{H^*_{\mathrm{crys}}} respects GF(3) grading.}
  \li{[[stk-0050]] \strong{de Rham Cohomology} --- The de Rham--Witt complex #{W\Omega^*_{X/\mathbb{F}_3}} computes crystalline cohomology. The trit conservation law is a cycle condition in degree 0.}
  \li{[[stk-0061]] \strong{Pro-etale Cohomology} --- The pro-etale site gives access to #{\mathbb{F}_3}-coefficients without lifting. #{H^0_{\mathrm{proet}}(X, \mathbb{F}_3)} detects the GF(3) invariant.}
  \li{[[stk-0009]] \strong{Fields} --- #{\mathbb{F}_3} is the smallest field where #{-1 \neq 1}. This is why GF(3) --- not GF(2) --- captures the ternary logic of inhibition/activation/crossover.}
}

\p{The conservation law #{\sum \mathrm{trit}(U_i) = 0 \pmod{3}} is a global section of the constant sheaf #{\underline{\mathbb{F}_3}} on the BCI pipeline scheme. Its non-vanishing would be a cohomological obstruction to pipeline integrity.}
